Masks are essential for preventing the spread of COVID19 during the pandemic and

have become an everyday accessory Alarmingly from what we have observed people

are discarding masks along the roadside beach sides and even empty shopping

trolleys causing a hazard to animals and the environment

The environments in danger of being another victim if masks are not disposed of

carefully A large number of surgical masks are found lying along the roadside in open

areas and this is a threat to the next person and the wildlife in most cases discarded

masks may risk spreading the corona virus to waste collectors litter pickers or mem

bers of the public who first come across the litter

However more importantly failure to disposing of masks properly affects animals in

the process Some animals cannot tell the difference between plastic items and their

prey subsequently choking on pieces of litter They might not choke but can become

malnourished as the materials fill up their stomachs but provide no nutrients Smatler

animals may also become entangled in the elastic within the masks

How to dispose of single masks correctly

According to WHO fold mask Into half inwards such that droplets from the mouth

and nose are not exposed Then fold inte another half until it looks like a roll The mask

can be wrapped with its ear loops so that it will not unravel Then wrap the mask ina

tissue paper or polythene bag and immediately dispose of it

Orsimply

Cut off strings fold and place into a small plastic and dispose carefully

Cut off inner linen and dispose inta a bin

NB Always make sure you place your mask in a plastic or paper bag and dispose
